          "order": 0,
          "props": {
            "title": "How sourdough taught me patience",
            "excerpt": "I used to think baking was about precision — weigh the flour to the gram, hit the oven temperature exactly, set a timer for every step. That worked for cookies and cakes. Then I tried sourdough, and sourdough laughed at my timers. The first three loaves were bricks. I followed a famous recipe to the letter and got a famously bad result. The problem wasn't the recipe — it was that I kept reading the clock instead of reading the dough. Around loaf number seven, I stopped looking at the clock and started watching the dough: how it sprang back, how the surface went from tacky to satiny, how the bubbles climbed the bowl. The next loaf had ears. Sourdough didn't teach me a recipe — it taught me to slow down enough to notice what was actually happening in front of me.",
            "author": "Bradley",
            "date": "2026-04-15",
            "tags": "baking, sourdough, patience",
            "featuredImage": "/images/sourdough-1.jpg"
          }
        }
      ],
